        <div class="life">
            <p class="life-header bold">
                Here is a time line of Johnny Cash's life:
            </p>
            <ul id="tribute-info">
               <li><span class="bold">1932 - </span>Born in Kingsland, Arkansas</li>
               <li><span class="bold">1950 - </span>He enlisted in the Air Force. After basic training he was assinged to the 12th Radio Squadron Moble of the U.S Air Force Security Service</li>
               <li><span class="bold">1955 - </span>He made his first recordings such as "Hey Porter" "Cry! Cry! Cry!"</li>
               <li><span class="bold">1957 - </span>He recorded "Folsom Prison Blue"</li>
               <li><span class="bold">1958 - </span>Cash left Phillips to sign a lucrative offer with Columbia Records. His single "Don't Take Your Guns to Town" became one of his biggest hits, and he recorded a collection of gospel songs for his second album for Columbia</li>
               <li><span class="bold">1960 - </span>Cash toured with the Carter Family</li>
               <li><span class="bold">1965 - </span>Cash's camper caught fire during a fishing trip with his nephew Damon Fielder in Los Padres National Forest in California, triggering a forest fire that burned several hundred acres and nearly caused his death</li>
               <li><span class="bold">1967 - </span>Cash's duet with June Carter, "Jackson", won a Grammy Award</li>
               <li><span class="bold">1968 - </span>Cash proposed onstage to June, at a concert at the London Gardens in London, Ontario, Canada</li>
               <li><span class="bold">1970 - </span>Cash did not end all drug use until</li>
               <li><span class="bold">1970 - </span>Cash had established his public image as the "Man in Black". He regularly performed in entirely black suits with a long, black, knee-length coat</li>
               <li><span class="bold">1971 - </span>Cash starred in his own television show, The Johnny Cash Show, on the ABC network</li>
               <li><span class="bold">1975 - </span>His first autobiography, Man in Black, was published</li>
               <li><span class="bold">1977 - </span>Cash began using amphetamines again</li>
               <li><span class="bold">1980 - </span>Cash became the Country Music Hall of Fame's youngest living inductee at age 48</li>
               <li><span class="bold">1989 - </span>He was dependent and entered Nashville's Cumberland Heights Alcohol and Drug Treatment Center</li>
               <li><span class="bold">1992 - </span>He started care at the Loma Linda Behavioral Medicine Center in Loma Linda, California, for his final rehabilitation treatment.</li>
               <li><span class="bold">1997 - </span>Cash was diagnosed with the neurodegenerative disease Shy-Drager syndrome, a form of multiple system atrophy</li>
               <li><span class="bold">2003 - </span>Died aged 71 in Nadhville, Tennessee</li>
               <li><span class="bold">2005 - </span>A chronicle of country music legend Johnny Cash's life, from his early days on an Arkansas cotton farm to his rise to fame
            </li>
            </ul>  
            <div class="quote-container">
                <p class="quote">"People call me wild. Not really though, I'm not. I guess I've never been normal, not what you call Establishment. I'm country."
                </p>
                <p class="quote-author">-- Johnny Cash</p>
            </div>  
